{%- comment -%}
  Back-in-Stock Notification — modal + form.

  Rendered next to the disabled add-to-cart button on the PDP /
  featured product when the selected variant is unavailable. Lets
  the customer drop their email so the merchant can notify them
  when the variant is restocked.

  Backend: Shopify's native `{% form 'contact' %}` block. The form
  POSTs to the customer-contact endpoint, which surfaces the
  submission in Admin → Settings → Notifications → Customer
  contact AND triggers Shopify's "New customer contact submission"
  email to the store owner. Merchants can pipe this into Klaviyo /
  Mailchimp via Shopify Flow without any theme-side integration.

  Hidden message field auto-fills product title + currently-selected
  option values + product URL so the merchant sees exactly WHICH
  variant the customer is waiting on. Without this context the
  notification reduces to "someone wanted a thing" — useless for
  restock prioritisation.

  Accepts:
  - product       (required) Product object
  - variant       (optional) Selected variant; defaults to selected_or_first_available
  - section_id    (required) Section identifier for unique IDs
  - heading       (optional) Modal heading override
  - description   (optional) Richtext copy shown above the form
  - show_name     (optional, bool) Render the optional name field
  - show_phone    (optional, bool) Render the optional phone field
  - render_mode   (optional) 'trigger' | 'modal' | 'both' (default 'both').
                  When the caller is INSIDE another <form> (e.g. the
                  product-form's <form action="/cart/add">), the modal's
                  inner `{% form 'contact' %}` becomes invalid nested
                  markup — HTML5 parsers ignore the inner <form> tag and
                  re-parent the email input + submit button onto the
                  OUTER form. The Notify-me button then silently posts
                  to /cart/add instead of /contact and the customer
                  sees "nothing happens". Use render_mode: 'trigger'
                  inside the form (just the button) and render_mode:
                  'modal' AFTER the form's {% endform %} (just the
                  modal). The JS pairs them via [data-modal-target=ID].
{%- endcomment -%}

{%- liquid
  unless variant
    assign variant = product.selected_or_first_available_variant
  endunless
  unless render_mode
    assign render_mode = 'both'
  endunless
  assign form_id = 'BackInStockForm-' | append: section_id | append: '-' | append: product.id
  assign trigger_id = 'BackInStockTrigger-' | append: section_id | append: '-' | append: product.id
  assign modal_id = 'BackInStockModal-' | append: section_id | append: '-' | append: product.id
  assign title_id = 'BackInStockTitle-' | append: section_id | append: '-' | append: product.id
  assign return_to = variant.url | default: product.url
  assign safe_product_title = product.title | escape
-%}

{%- if render_mode == 'trigger' or render_mode == 'both' -%}
<button
  type="button"
  id="{{ trigger_id }}"
  class="kt-back-in-stock__trigger"
  data-back-in-stock-trigger
  data-modal-target="{{ modal_id }}"
  aria-haspopup="dialog"
  aria-controls="{{ modal_id }}"
  {% if variant.available %}hidden{% endif %}
>
  {%- comment -%}
    Small mail icon next to the label keeps the button readable as
    a notification opt-in rather than another buy/secondary action.
  {%- endcomment -%}
  <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="16" height="16" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
    <path d="M4 4h16c1.1 0 2 .9 2 2v12c0 1.1-.9 2-2 2H4c-1.1 0-2-.9-2-2V6c0-1.1.9-2 2-2z"></path>
    <polyline points="22,6 12,13 2,6"></polyline>
  </svg>
  <span>{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.notify_me' | t | default: 'Notify me when available' }}</span>
</button>
{%- endif -%}

{%- if render_mode == 'modal' or render_mode == 'both' -%}
<div
  id="{{ modal_id }}"
  class="kt-back-in-stock__modal"
  data-back-in-stock-modal
  role="dialog"
  aria-modal="true"
  aria-labelledby="{{ title_id }}"
  aria-hidden="true"
  inert
  data-lenis-prevent="true"
>
  <div class="kt-back-in-stock__backdrop" data-back-in-stock-close></div>
  <div class="kt-back-in-stock__panel" role="document">
    <button
      type="button"
      class="kt-back-in-stock__close"
      data-back-in-stock-close
      aria-label="{{ 'kt.a11y.close' | t | default: 'Close' }}"
    >
      <svg aria-hidden="true" focusable="false" width="18" height="18" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.75" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <line x1="18" y1="6" x2="6" y2="18"></line>
        <line x1="6" y1="6" x2="18" y2="18"></line>
      </svg>
    </button>

    <header class="kt-back-in-stock__header">
      {%- comment -%}
        Header groups the icon + heading + description so the panel
        reads as a focused notification capture surface rather than
        a stack of disconnected text blocks. The bell glyph adds a
        small piece of visual furniture above the heading without
        adding meaningful UI weight.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <span class="kt-back-in-stock__icon" aria-hidden="true">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
          <path d="M6 8a6 6 0 0 1 12 0c0 7 3 9 3 9H3s3-2 3-9"/>
          <path d="M10.3 21a1.94 1.94 0 0 0 3.4 0"/>
        </svg>
      </span>
      <h2 id="{{ title_id }}" class="kt-back-in-stock__heading">
        {%- if heading != blank -%}
          {{ heading | escape }}
        {%- else -%}
          {{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.heading' | t | default: 'Notify me when back in stock' }}
        {%- endif -%}
      </h2>
      {%- if description != blank -%}
        <div class="kt-back-in-stock__description rte">{{ description }}</div>
      {%- else -%}
        <p class="kt-back-in-stock__description">
          {{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.description' | t | default: 'Drop your email and we will let you know the moment this item is available again.' }}
        </p>
      {%- endif -%}
    </header>

    <div class="kt-back-in-stock__product">
      {%- comment -%}
        Product thumbnail anchors the "which item are you watching"
        question visually. Falls through to the product placeholder
        when the merchant hasn't set a featured image yet so the
        layout never collapses to text-only.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="kt-back-in-stock__product-media">
        {%- if product.featured_image != blank -%}
          {{
            product.featured_image
            | image_url: width: 160
            | image_tag:
              loading: 'lazy',
              widths: '64, 96, 128, 160',
              sizes: '64px',
              width: 64,
              height: 64,
              alt: safe_product_title,
              class: 'kt-back-in-stock__product-image'
          }}
        {%- else -%}
          {{ 'product-1' | placeholder_svg_tag: 'placeholder-svg kt-back-in-stock__product-image' }}
        {%- endif -%}
      </div>
      <div class="kt-back-in-stock__product-body">
        <span class="kt-back-in-stock__product-label">{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.product_label' | t | default: 'Item' }}</span>
        <strong class="kt-back-in-stock__product-title" data-back-in-stock-product-title>{{ safe_product_title }}</strong>
        {%- unless product.has_only_default_variant -%}
          <span class="kt-back-in-stock__variant" data-back-in-stock-variant-title>{{ variant.title | escape }}</span>
        {%- endunless -%}
      </div>
    </div>

    {%- form 'contact', id: form_id, class: 'kt-back-in-stock__form' -%}
      {%- comment -%}
        return_to query param flags a posted submission so the
        success state below can detect it on page reload. Shopify's
        `{% form 'contact' %}` natively redirects back to the URL
        in `return_to`; `?contact_posted=true` is the canonical
        marker reference themes use.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <input type="hidden" name="return_to" value="{{ return_to }}{% if return_to contains '?' %}&{% else %}?{% endif %}contact_posted=true">

      {%- if form.errors -%}
        <div class="kt-back-in-stock__alert kt-back-in-stock__alert--error" role="alert">
          {{ form.errors | default_errors }}
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if form.posted_successfully? -%}
        <div class="kt-back-in-stock__alert kt-back-in-stock__alert--success" role="status" data-back-in-stock-success>
          {{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.success' | t | default: 'Thanks — we will email you the moment this item is back.' }}
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if show_name -%}
        <div class="kt-back-in-stock__field">
          <label for="{{ form_id }}-name">{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.name_label' | t | default: 'Name' }}</label>
          <input
            type="text"
            id="{{ form_id }}-name"
            name="contact[name]"
            autocomplete="name"
            value="{% if form.name %}{{ form.name | escape }}{% elsif customer %}{{ customer.name | escape }}{% endif %}"
          >
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      {%- if show_phone -%}
        <div class="kt-back-in-stock__field">
          <label for="{{ form_id }}-phone">{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.phone_label' | t | default: 'Phone' }}</label>
          <input
            type="tel"
            inputmode="tel"
            id="{{ form_id }}-phone"
            name="contact[phone]"
            autocomplete="tel"
            value="{% if form.phone %}{{ form.phone | escape }}{% elsif customer %}{{ customer.phone | escape }}{% endif %}"
          >
        </div>
      {%- endif -%}

      <div class="kt-back-in-stock__field">
        <label for="{{ form_id }}-email">{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.email_label' | t | default: 'Email' }}</label>
        <input
          type="email"
          id="{{ form_id }}-email"
          name="contact[email]"
          autocomplete="email"
          spellcheck="false"
          autocapitalize="off"
          required
          aria-required="true"
          value="{% if form.email %}{{ form.email | escape }}{% elsif customer %}{{ customer.email | escape }}{% endif %}"
        >
      </div>

      {%- comment -%}
        Hidden message field — the contact form's body. Auto-fills
        product context so the merchant sees the EXACT variant the
        customer requested. Reference theme pattern: title + each
        option's selected value + the product URL on a fresh line.
        `data-back-in-stock-message` lets product-form.js refresh
        the variant portion when the customer changes options
        without leaving the modal.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <textarea
        name="contact[{{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.message_label' | t | default: 'Restock request' }}]"
        class="kt-back-in-stock__hidden-message"
        data-back-in-stock-message
        hidden
        aria-hidden="true"
        tabindex="-1"
      >
{{- safe_product_title -}}
{%- unless product.has_only_default_variant %}
{% for option in product.options_with_values %}{{ option.name | escape }}: {% for value in option.values %}{% if option.selected_value == value %}{{ value | escape }}{% endif %}{% endfor %}{% unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless %}{% endfor %}{%- endunless %}
{{ request.origin }}{{ return_to }}
      </textarea>

      <button type="submit" class="kt-back-in-stock__submit">
        {{ 'kt.product.back_in_stock.submit' | t | default: 'Notify me' }}
      </button>

      {%- comment -%}
        Shopify's spam-detection disclaimer is required when the
        form posts to the contact endpoint with reCAPTCHA active.
        Without it the small reCAPTCHA widget paints in the
        bottom-right corner of every page that renders this form,
        which Theme Store reviewers flag as visual noise.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      {% comment %}theme-check-disable TranslationKeyExists{% endcomment %}
      {%- comment -%}
        Wrapper is intentionally a <div> rather than <p>. Shopify's
        `shopify.online_store.spam_detection.disclaimer_html`
        translation can ship its own block-level wrapping in some
        locales — when it does, the HTML parser auto-closes a
        nesting `<p>` before opening the inner one, which leaves
        the .kt-back-in-stock__legal class on an empty paragraph
        and the actual disclaimer text on a naked default-styled
        <p>. The <div> wrapper + descendant `p` / `a` selectors in
        the companion CSS guarantee the muted-fine-print treatment
        whether Shopify emits text-with-anchors or a wrapped block.
      {%- endcomment -%}
      <div class="kt-back-in-stock__legal">{{ 'shopify.online_store.spam_detection.disclaimer_html' | t }}</div>
      {% comment %}theme-check-enable TranslationKeyExists{% endcomment %}
    {%- endform -%}
  </div>
</div>
{%- endif -%}
